39
00:03:07,639 --> 00:03:11,782
This is where we had a group of senior developers and management to talk about the feature.

40
00:03:16,325 --> 00:03:19,368
Yeah, so I started thinking about this problem space, right?

41
00:03:19,508 --> 00:03:21,169
Of, well, what is it we're really trying to do?

42
00:03:21,229 --> 00:03:24,632
Are we trying to, you know, teach somebody how to play a guitar who's never played one before?

43
00:03:24,732 --> 00:03:27,754
Or is it just really about playing Rock Band with a guitar?

44
00:03:28,975 --> 00:03:31,937
And when I started thinking about this, I realized that they don't actually intersect that much.

45
00:03:32,518 --> 00:03:33,498
And to compound things...

46
00:03:34,182 --> 00:03:35,963
The sort of feedback that we're going to need to give,

47
00:03:36,483 --> 00:03:37,784
the information we're going to need to display,

48
00:03:37,844 --> 00:03:41,145
actually radically changes as somebody becomes more comfortable with a guitar.

49
00:03:42,846 --> 00:03:45,747
So right off the bat, we established our target audience

50
00:03:45,807 --> 00:03:48,708
as being sort of the hard-to-expert rock band players,

51
00:03:48,728 --> 00:03:50,709
the people who have been, you know, playing a lot of our game,

52
00:03:50,729 --> 00:03:52,810
but they didn't necessarily have guitar experience,

53
00:03:52,850 --> 00:03:53,790
but were interested in learning.

54
00:03:54,851 --> 00:03:57,772
And we set a sort of modest goal of like, hey, you know,

55
00:03:58,272 --> 00:04:01,394
If these guys are able to sort of play a campfire version of songs at the end of this,

56
00:04:01,454 --> 00:04:02,695
then we've kind of won, right?

57
00:04:02,735 --> 00:04:07,878
If we can get them to play, you know, a couple song version of, you know, a couple chord version of some song,

58
00:04:07,898 --> 00:04:12,361
then they're going to feel really good, and maybe they'll go on and learn more about guitar and music.

59
00:04:13,742 --> 00:04:17,344
And sort of our approach was to use this sort of ramp we have in our games,

60
00:04:17,384 --> 00:04:19,926
where you start out on easy and you're playing a very simplified version,

61
00:04:20,246 --> 00:04:22,708
and you work your way up to a much more complex version over time.

62
00:04:23,788 --> 00:04:27,411
Another sort of initial decision was we have this great illusion in our games.

63
00:04:28,038 --> 00:04:31,039
The first time you play, you know, the first time you play Guitar Hero or Rock Band,

64
00:04:31,059 --> 00:04:34,821
you hit some silly little gem, you know, representation on this guitar,

65
00:04:34,861 --> 00:04:36,702
and then this huge sound comes out of the speaker.

66
00:04:36,722 --> 00:04:38,523
And that's really rewarding to players.

67
00:04:39,363 --> 00:04:42,565
So rather than, you know, the traditional instrument learning experience

68
00:04:42,585 --> 00:04:44,846
where the first sound you make actually sounds really horrible,

69
00:04:45,346 --> 00:04:47,687
we were going to use that illusion, so the first time you get something right,

70
00:04:47,747 --> 00:04:50,528
you got that big sort of feedback.

71
00:04:54,590 --> 00:04:55,130
Okay, so...

72
00:04:55,746 --> 00:04:58,988
There's a lot of ideas and there's a large possibility space at this time.

73
00:05:00,069 --> 00:05:02,771
But the problem is, you know, Harmonics is a big company and we have a lot of projects,

74
00:05:02,811 --> 00:05:05,833
and at this point we didn't actually have coding resources to get things in the game.

75
00:05:07,134 --> 00:05:11,156
So what we did was we explored the space as much as we could, you know, with designers

76
00:05:11,176 --> 00:05:15,059
and artists, design docs, pictures, and video. I'm going to show you some of that stuff right

77
00:05:15,079 --> 00:05:20,242
now. So as a quick primer, for those of you who

78
00:05:20,262 --> 00:05:23,825
don't play guitar, if you're looking at a guitar neck, it has these raised metal objects

79
00:05:23,885 --> 00:05:24,405
called frets.

80
00:05:25,736 --> 00:05:29,377
You push the string down behind the fret, and then you pluck the string with your other

81
00:05:29,417 --> 00:05:33,298
hand, and that actually will make sounds. And as you move your finger along different

82
00:05:33,358 --> 00:05:35,318
frets, you'll actually make different types of sounds.

83
00:05:36,719 --> 00:05:41,400
On a rock band guitar, this is actually replicated by the five buttons. They represent five different

84
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:46,421
frets. So when you're holding the second red button, you can see that that is replicating

85
00:05:46,821 --> 00:05:49,482
holding down behind the second fret and picking a string.

86
00:05:51,122 --> 00:05:54,003
So we call this fret relative. As you move from left to right,

87
00:05:54,427 --> 00:05:56,789
You're actually moving up from the first to the fifth fret.

88
00:05:57,369 --> 00:05:59,751
And these things coming down the track, which we call gems,

89
00:06:00,172 --> 00:06:01,453
are colored to represent that.

90
00:06:01,813 --> 00:06:04,856
When you have to hit that, as it crosses the bar at the bottom,

91
00:06:05,256 --> 00:06:05,937
you're hitting a fret.

92
00:06:06,197 --> 00:06:08,379
So this red one coming down, that's the second fret

93
00:06:08,399 --> 00:06:08,919
you'd have to hit.

94
00:06:09,600 --> 00:06:10,741
And time is the next axis.

95
00:06:12,562 --> 00:06:15,265
One of the things we wanted to experiment with first

96
00:06:15,425 --> 00:06:18,728
is the idea of fret relative, because millions of our players

97
00:06:18,748 --> 00:06:20,469
have been playing this game.

98
00:06:21,301 --> 00:06:22,802
We kind of baked this knowledge into them.

99
00:06:22,822 --> 00:06:24,602
We thought this might be the first thing we should try.

100
00:06:26,463 --> 00:06:28,844
So here's an example from an early design document.

101
00:06:28,864 --> 00:06:30,805
You can see on the top, if the player was

102
00:06:31,025 --> 00:06:33,646
to be playing a real guitar, in this example,

103
00:06:34,026 --> 00:06:36,127
the third position represents the third fret.

104
00:06:36,547 --> 00:06:38,508
So the player would be holding the third fret

105
00:06:38,528 --> 00:06:39,249
with his left hand.

106
00:06:39,569 --> 00:06:41,229
And each of these gems have a color on it.

107
00:06:41,289 --> 00:06:43,270
And the color represents which string you'd have to hit.

108
00:06:43,831 --> 00:06:44,611
So in this example.

109
00:06:45,158 --> 00:06:49,020
I'm holding the third fret, and on the green one, I'd have to hit the lowest string.

110
00:06:49,220 --> 00:06:51,541
On the red one, I'd have to hit the next string up from that.

111
00:06:53,742 --> 00:06:57,264
Here's another example of that, where color and position represent which fret you'd have

112
00:06:57,284 --> 00:06:59,805
to hit. The string position, you can see on the gems,

113
00:06:59,865 --> 00:07:04,568
is represented by stars in this example. Or, actually, there's numbers that are not

114
00:07:04,628 --> 00:07:09,330
represented there that we could have tried. So we quickly moved into videos.

115
00:07:10,371 --> 00:07:13,352
Here's a 3D Studio Max mockup that our artist made.

116
00:07:14,617 --> 00:07:16,778
It's always good to do a max mockup with real data.

117
00:07:17,218 --> 00:07:18,319
In our case, this is songs.

