00:07:19,240 --> 00:07:20,040
Let me turn up a tiny bit.

119
00:07:20,541 --> 00:07:21,041
Can you guys hear that?

120
00:07:23,903 --> 00:07:31,288
So this max mockup, you can see, kind of was hard to understand

121
00:07:31,328 --> 00:07:32,268
and kind of hard to read, right?

122
00:07:33,029 --> 00:07:34,090
It's a pretty standard song.

123
00:07:34,510 --> 00:07:35,771
And there's a lot of stuff going on.

124
00:07:35,791 --> 00:07:38,292
And this convinced a lot of us that maybe fret relative

125
00:07:38,332 --> 00:07:39,373
was not the best approach.

126
00:07:42,950 --> 00:07:44,870
Then we started thinking about the idea of string relative.

127
00:07:44,910 --> 00:07:47,251
If you turn the guitar neck 90 degrees,

128
00:07:47,671 --> 00:07:49,052
instead of looking at the frets,

129
00:07:49,152 --> 00:07:50,432
you're now looking down the fretboard.

130
00:07:51,213 --> 00:07:52,893
You'd have your lowest strings on one side

131
00:07:52,933 --> 00:07:54,314
and your highest strings on the other side.

132
00:07:54,974 --> 00:07:56,615
Gems coming down, instead of telling you,

133
00:07:56,935 --> 00:07:58,215
coming down what fret they would on,

134
00:07:58,335 --> 00:07:59,576
they would come down and tell you

135
00:07:59,596 --> 00:08:00,796
which string you have to play on.

136
00:08:01,056 --> 00:08:03,217
And something about the gem would have to represent

137
00:08:03,437 --> 00:08:05,138
what fret to play instead of what string.

138
00:08:06,078 --> 00:08:07,979
So, let's look at one example here.

139
00:08:08,019 --> 00:08:09,540
This is an early art mock-up.

