00:09:03,553 --> 00:09:04,773
to understand in this way.

161
00:09:06,332 --> 00:09:08,233
This video gave us a little bit more confidence

162
00:09:08,773 --> 00:09:09,773
coming towards the next period.

163
00:09:10,354 --> 00:09:13,675
In fact, with this, we were able to work with management

164
00:09:13,735 --> 00:09:15,055
and senior developers in the company

165
00:09:15,255 --> 00:09:17,136
to come up with our minimum goals and constraints

166
00:09:17,156 --> 00:09:17,656
for the system.

167
00:09:18,136 --> 00:09:20,317
Pro Guitar had to display notes and chords on the track.

168
00:09:20,737 --> 00:09:21,897
It had to be pitch accurate, means

169
00:09:22,297 --> 00:09:23,378
you never play the wrong note.

170
00:09:23,398 --> 00:09:24,558
We want to teach people the right thing.

171
00:09:25,619 --> 00:09:27,659
It had to target non-musician rock band players,

172
00:09:27,719 --> 00:09:29,220
as Jason said before, people that were looking

173
00:09:29,260 --> 00:09:29,860
for a new challenge.

174
00:09:31,120 --> 00:09:32,761
It didn't necessarily have to work with bass.

175
00:09:33,960 --> 00:09:36,522
It didn't necessarily have to work with all the Rock Band 3 songs.

176
00:09:36,722 --> 00:09:38,643
We were targeting maybe, say, 20 of the 80.

177
00:09:40,164 --> 00:09:41,925
And it didn't have to work in all game modes.

178
00:09:41,965 --> 00:09:43,927
It could be its own menu option off the main screen,

179
00:09:44,187 --> 00:09:44,888
if we needed it to be.

180
00:09:47,309 --> 00:09:49,351
So, our takeaway here is,

181
00:09:50,171 --> 00:09:52,813
when we had low resources,

182
00:09:53,434 --> 00:09:55,955
we used whatever we could to actually learn about the problem space.

183
00:09:56,236 --> 00:09:57,897
You know, getting things in the game is always best.

184
00:09:58,337 --> 00:10:00,058
But if we can't, we like video.

185
00:10:00,554 --> 00:10:03,876
And pictures and text are also useful to find more information.

186
00:10:05,837 --> 00:10:07,958
So the next period we're going to talk about is the prototyping period.

187
00:10:08,338 --> 00:10:10,940
This lasted for about seven months of the almost two-year period.

188
00:10:13,662 --> 00:10:15,943
So the problem space here is we need to iterate really fast.

189
00:10:16,003 --> 00:10:17,604
We want to get things in the game to try it.

190
00:10:17,985 --> 00:10:19,966
And we had a large group, and when you have a large group,

191
00:10:19,986 --> 00:10:22,968
there's a lot of disagreements about what you want to try and get in the game first.

192
00:10:23,548 --> 00:10:27,471
So one of the first things Dan did as strike leader at this point in time

193
00:10:27,891 --> 00:10:29,872
was reduce this group to a smaller size.

194
00:10:30,869 --> 00:10:35,971
We added Jason Booth and Mike Monselvatch, as Jason was our coder on the team.

195
00:10:36,771 --> 00:10:39,753
Jason is a multi-talented coder that can do anything we needed him to do.

196
00:10:40,093 --> 00:10:44,455
Jason can do graphics, gameplay, menu work, and Mike is similar as an artist.

197
00:10:44,495 --> 00:10:47,996
He can do 2D, 3D. These guys can do tons of iteration really fast.

198
00:10:51,858 --> 00:10:54,579
So, I went into this a little bit already.

199
00:10:54,699 --> 00:10:58,441
The best part of SmallStrike Team is the implementers are the people doing the work.

200
00:10:59,952 --> 00:11:01,212
Jason and Mike are able to do all that.

201
00:11:02,072 --> 00:11:03,773
I was able to contribute wherever I can,

202
00:11:04,553 --> 00:11:06,914
whether it's meeting notes or lesson designs or song ideas

203
00:11:06,994 --> 00:11:08,695
or art mock-ups.

204
00:11:10,376 --> 00:11:12,837
Another thing is we were able to have more focused meetings.

205
00:11:12,857 --> 00:11:14,957
We'd get things in the game, meet about it right away,

206
00:11:14,997 --> 00:11:16,618
and decide a course of action after that.

